21 Tool Calling
***************

21.1 Overview
=============

Tool calling (also known as function calling) enables LLMs to invoke
Emacs functions during conversations.  Instead of just generating text,
a tool-capable model can read files, list directories, search buffers,
perform calculations, and execute shell commands -- all orchestrated
automatically within the conversation flow.

   The tool calling framework is provided by ‘ollama-buddy-tools.el’.

21.2 Setup
==========

     ;; Load the tools module
     (require 'ollama-buddy-tools)

     ;; Enable tool calling
     (setq ollama-buddy-tools-enabled t)

   You must use a model that supports tool calling.  Tool-capable models
are indicated with a ‘⚒’ symbol in the header line, model selection, and
model management buffer.

21.3 Built-in Tools
===================

21.3.1 Safe Tools (available in safe mode)
------------------------------------------

‘read_file’
     Read the contents of a file from the filesystem.

‘list_directory’
     List the contents of a directory.

‘get_buffer_content’
     Get the content of an Emacs buffer by name.

‘list_buffers’
     List all open Emacs buffers, with optional regex filtering.

‘calculate’
     Evaluate a mathematical expression using Emacs ‘calc-eval’.

‘search_buffer’
     Search for a regex pattern in a buffer and return matching lines.

21.3.2 Unsafe Tools (require safe mode off)
-------------------------------------------

‘write_file’
     Write content to a file on the filesystem.

‘execute_shell’
     Execute a shell command and return its output.

21.4 Example Prompts
====================

With a tool-capable model selected and tools enabled, try prompts like:

     What files are in my ~/Documents directory?

     Read the file ~/.emacs.d/init.el and summarize what packages I'm using.

     What is 2^64 - 1?

     What buffers do I have open?

     Search for all defun definitions in the buffer ollama-buddy-tools.el

   For unsafe tools (with safe mode disabled):

     Run df -h and tell me how much disk space I have.

     Create a file at /tmp/hello.txt with Hello World.

21.5 How It Works
=================

When tool calling is enabled and a tool-capable model is selected, the
conversation flow works as follows:

  1. You send a prompt (e.g., "What files are in my home directory?").
  2. Ollama Buddy sends the prompt along with the tool schemas to the
     model.
  3. The model decides whether to call a tool.  If so, it returns a tool
     call request instead of text.
  4. Ollama Buddy executes the requested tool (e.g., ‘list_directory’
     with path ‘~’).
  5. The tool result is sent back to the model as a ‘tool’ role message.
  6. The model generates a natural language response incorporating the
     tool output.
  7. Steps 3-6 may repeat if the model needs multiple tools, up to
     ‘ollama-buddy-tools-max-iterations’.

   This loop is transparent to the user -- you see the final response in
the chat buffer.

21.6 Configuration
==================

‘ollama-buddy-tools-enabled’
     Whether tool calling is active (default: ‘nil’).

‘ollama-buddy-tools-safe-mode’
     When non-nil, only safe (read-only) tools can execute (default:
     ‘t’).

‘ollama-buddy-tools-auto-execute’
     When non-nil, tools execute without confirmation prompts (default:
     ‘t’).  When nil, each tool invocation shows a ‘yes-or-no-p’ prompt
     before executing.

‘ollama-buddy-tools-max-iterations’
     Maximum tool-call round-trips per user prompt to prevent infinite
     loops (default: ‘10’).

‘ollama-buddy-tools-builtin-enabled’
     Whether to load the 8 built-in tools on startup (default: ‘t’).
     When nil, only custom user-registered tools are available.

‘ollama-buddy-tools-models’
     List of model names known to support tool calling.  Used for the
     ‘⚒’ indicator.
          (setq ollama-buddy-tools-models
            '("qwen3" "qwen3-coder" "llama3.1" "llama3.3"
              "mistral" "gpt-oss" "command-r"))

21.7 Registering Custom Tools
=============================

Use ‘ollama-buddy-tools-register’ to add your own tools:

     (ollama-buddy-tools-register
      'my-tool                          ; NAME (symbol or string)
      "Description of what the tool does" ; DESCRIPTION
      '((type . "object")               ; PARAMETERS (JSON schema)
        (required . ["param1"])
        (properties . ((param1 . ((type . "string")
                                   (description . "Parameter description"))))))
      (lambda (args)                    ; FUNCTION (receives alist, returns string)
        (let ((param1 (alist-get 'param1 args)))
          (format "Result: %s" param1)))
      t)  ; SAFE flag: t = safe (read-only), nil = unsafe

   To remove a tool:
     (ollama-buddy-tools-unregister 'my-tool)

   The tool function receives an alist of arguments parsed from the
model's JSON response and must return a string result.  If the function
returns a non-string value, it is formatted with ‘%S’.

21.8 Interactive Commands
=========================

‘ollama-buddy-tools-toggle’
     Toggle tool calling on or off.

‘ollama-buddy-tools-toggle-safe-mode’
     Toggle safe mode for tool execution.

‘ollama-buddy-tools-info’
     Display information about all registered tools in a dedicated
     buffer, showing status, safe mode, and each tool's description.

‘ollama-buddy-tools-clear’
     Remove all registered tools.

‘ollama-buddy-tools-setup’
     Re-initialize built-in tools.

21.9 Tool-Capable Model Indicator
=================================

Models known to support tool calling show a ‘⚒’ indicator in:

   • The header line when the current model supports tools
   • The ‘C-c m’ completing-read model selector (alongside ‘⊙’ for
     vision models)
   • The model management buffer (‘C-c M’) next to model names

   The list of tool-capable models is configured via
‘ollama-buddy-tools-models’.  Cloud model variants (e.g.
‘cl:qwen3-coder:480b-cloud’) are automatically matched against their
base names.


